\subtree{\title{Current: 222 Dore Street}
\meta{status}{operational}
\meta{rent}{$4,000/mo ($2,000/office × 2)}
\meta{offices}{2}
\meta{floor}{upstairs}

\p{222 Dore Street, San Francisco. Showplace Square. Walk Score 98, Transit Score 99, Bike Score 99. Two upstairs offices at $2,000/month each. The BCI Factory's operating base since early 2026.}

\subtree{\title{BCI Bench}
\p{One dedicated BCI recording station. OpenBCI Cyton 8ch (250 Hz), conductive gel, impedance meter, laptop running Emacs kiosk with real-time topomap. Walk-in readings: 2-minute protocol, deterministic color hash output via SplitMix64. The bench fits in a single office — shitty signal is better than no signal.}}

\subtree{\title{Second Office}
\p{Firmware development, signal analysis, compute. Offline processing of recordings from the BCI bench. The computational back-end.}}}

\subtree{\title{Expansion Target: 250 Dore Street}
\meta{status}{available for lease — immediate}
\meta{sqft}{14,543}
\meta{broker}{Kevin Pon / Evan Housel, Kidder Mathews}
\meta{building-year}{1984}
\meta{history}{Fletcher Benton sculpture studio}
\meta{sold}{$3,750,000 on Dec 1, 2025}
\meta{deposit-available}{$120,000}

\p{250 Dore Street. Less than 100 feet from 222 Dore — same block. 14,543 SF standalone building, currently empty and listed for lease through Kidder Mathews. Built in 1984/85 by sculptor Fletcher Benton as his creative retreat. Sold Dec 2025 for $3.75M (28.6\% below $5.25M ask). The full-scale instantiation of Victor and Iannini's communal science lab.}

\subtree{\title{Ground Floor: The Lab}
\meta{sqft}{6638}
\meta{ceiling-ft}{34}
\p{6,638 square feet. 34-foot ceilings. Polished concrete. 16-foot roll-up door to the street. This is where the full BCI stack would live. Stations arranged for visibility and collaboration. When someone is recording EEG, the topomaps project onto the wall — anyone walking through can see the signal.}
\p{Adjacent sculpture garden becomes outdoor experiment space. Ecological validity by default.}}

\subtree{\title{Mezzanine: Compute}
\meta{sqft}{2073}
\p{2,073 square feet. Gensyn RL swarm node. GPU racks for decentralized training. Firmware development. The computational engine.}}

\subtree{\title{Penthouse: Collaboration}
\meta{sqft}{5832}
\p{5,832 square feet. Open plan. Kitchen. 2 bed / 2 bath residential suite. Conference room for live demos — present results by putting the headset on. If the effect doesn't reproduce live, the presentation fails.}
\p{Roof deck with sweeping cityscape views — NE to downtown, SW to Twin Peaks. Decompression space.}}}

\subtree{\title{Why Dore Street}
\p{The communal science lab requires specific physical properties:}
\ul{
  \li{\strong{Existing presence}: already operating at 222 Dore with BCI bench — proven location}
  \li{\strong{Adjacency}: 250 Dore is next door — no relocation logistics, walk 30 seconds}
  \li{\strong{Volume}: 34-foot ceilings at 250 for projection and shared visibility}
  \li{\strong{Permeability}: 16-foot roll-up door, street-level access}
  \li{\strong{Density}: SoMa location, transit score 99}
  \li{\strong{Heritage}: Fletcher Benton built balanced, harmonious geometric sculptures here — GF(3) conservation is the same aesthetic in a new medium}
}
\p{The path: 222 Dore (now, $4K/mo, BCI bench) → 250 Dore ($120K deposit, 14,543 SF, full factory).}}
